      Elsewhere in crypto crime
   =20
 =20

I suppose if you are a law enforcement officer and a guy calls 911 and says=
 =E2=80=9Csomeone stole my Bitcoins,=E2=80=9D you could just go to his hous=
e and arrest him? Or at least show up and ask him questions like =E2=80=9Cw=
here did you last see your Bitcoins?=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdo you have any =
enemies?=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cis there any chance you acquired these Bitco=
ins by hacking a dark-web drug marketplace?=E2=80=9D
Here is a=C2=A0CNBC story about a guy named Jimmy Zhong, who called 911 bec=
ause someone stole his Bitcoins, and the cops showed up and were like =E2=
=80=9Cokay but who did=C2=A0you=C2=A0steal the Bitcoins from,=E2=80=9D and =
he was like =E2=80=9Coh Silk Road=E2=80=9D and they arrested him.=C2=A0No, =
I=E2=80=99m kidding, I=E2=80=99m condensing the timeline, and he didn=E2=80=
=99t actually say that, but that is where=C2=A0he stole the Bitcoins from, =
and they did ultimately arrest him for it. The scorecard here is:
=09The guy who stole hundreds of thousands of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of Zho=
ng=E2=80=99s Bitcoins was never caught.=09Zhong was sentenced to=C2=A0a yea=
r in prison for stealing billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of Silk Road=E2=
=80=99s Bitcoins.=09The guy who ran Silk Road was sentenced to life in pris=
on, mostly for running a marketplace selling drugs for Bitcoins though also=
 for trying to use Bitcoins to hire hitmen to do some murders.

The lesson might be that if you are going to do crypto crime, stealing from=
 people who steal from people who run crypto drug marketplaces is a better =
bet than running the marketplaces yourself. This is not any sort of advice =
at all.
Three other funny points from the CNBC story. One is that US law enforcemen=
t seized the Bitcoins that Zhong stole from Silk Road (except for the ones =
that were stolen from him) and very cleverly offered to return them to thei=
r rightful owners, opening =E2=80=9Ca process that allowed victims of the h=
ack to apply to get their bitcoin back.=E2=80=9D Again this is not legal ad=
vice, but do not fill out that application! Nobody did:
Nobody came forward to claim the loot. That=E2=80=99s not surprising, given=
 that users of Silk Road in 2012 were largely drug dealers and their custom=
ers.
Two, the government then =E2=80=9Csold off the stolen bitcoin and will keep=
 the proceeds.=E2=80=9D Zhong=E2=80=99s lawyers make the sensible point tha=
t, by stealing these Bitcoins from Silk Road and handing them over to the g=
overnment years later, Zhong actually made the government a lot of money:

=E2=80=9CIf Jimmy had not stolen the coins and the government had in fact s=
eized them from [Silk Road operator Ross Ulbricht] they would have sold the=
m two years later in 2014 as they did with other coins.=E2=80=9D
At that point, the government =E2=80=9Cwould have gotten $320 a coin or mad=
e somewhere about $14 million,=E2=80=9D Bachner said. =E2=80=9CNow, as a re=
sult of Jimmy having them, the government has gotten a $3 billion profit.=
=E2=80=9D

Over the last few years, a=C2=A0lot of people have made arguments with the =
essential form =E2=80=9CI am an investing genius because I held Bitcoin fro=
m 2014 through 2021,=E2=80=9D but this particular one struck me as novel.
Three, here=E2=80=99s how BlockTrace cyberintelligence investigator Shaun M=
aGruder knew that Zhong was the hacker:

