   =20
      Economic non-calls
   =20
 =20

Bank additional tier 1 capital securities are instruments that look sort of=
 like bonds and sort of like stock. They are like bonds in that they pay so=
me interest rate and are usually repaid at par after five to ten years. The=
y are like stock in that, if the bank=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0pay interes=
t, or=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0pay them back after five to ten years, noth=
ing happens: The holders of the AT1s can=E2=80=99t sue for their money or p=
ut the bank into bankruptcy; everything is kind of voluntary. (This oversim=
plifies the mechanics, but not by too much.)
The advantage of this structure is that banks can pitch it to investors as =
=E2=80=9Clook, a bond=E2=80=9D and pay a fairly low interest rate, and they=
 can pitch it to regulators as =E2=80=9Clook, equity=E2=80=9D and get a lot=
 of regulatory capital credit. I   wrote a few years ago: =E2=80=9CIf the r=
egulators think that they=E2=80=99re equity and the investors think that th=
ey=E2=80=99re debt, probably someone is wrong!=E2=80=9D And since then we h=
ave occasionally talked about   times when the investors are wrong. Most no=
tably when Credit Suisse Group AG was sold to UBS Group AG and Credit Suiss=
e shareholders got a small payment while its AT1 holders   got zeroed.
But=C2=A0most=C2=A0of the time investors are right: Most of the time banks =
pay their interest on AT1s, and repay them at the =E2=80=9Cfirst call date,=
=E2=80=9D the date, five to ten years after issuance, when the market=C2=A0=
expects=C2=A0them to mature. (Technically they have no maturity date becaus=
e the bank=C2=A0can=C2=A0keep them outstanding forever, but the bank usuall=
y pays them back at the first call.) In particular, because interest rates =
move, when an AT1 reaches its first call date, there are two possibilities:
=09Interest rates have gone down,
  [4]
=C2=A0so the bank can repay the AT1 and replace it with a new AT1 with a lo=
wer interest rate, or=09Interest rates have gone up, so if the bank repaid =
the AT1 it would have to replace it with a new AT1 with a=C2=A0higher=C2=A0=
interest rate.

In Possibility 1, the bank can and should repay the AT1 (and do a new cheap=
er one), and normally does. In Possibility 2, economically speaking, the ba=
nk=C2=A0shouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0repay the AT1: It should keep it outstanding=
 as cheap capital, rather than repaying it and issuing new, more expensive =
capital.
But in fact, in Possibility 2, banks almost always=C2=A0do=C2=A0repay their=
 AT1s, because that is more polite to AT1 investors, and banks want the goo=
dwill of AT1 investors, because they will be coming back to them for capita=
l. When   we first talked about AT1s around here, it was because Banco Sant=
ander SA did=C2=A0not=C2=A0repay its AT1s at the first call date, and there=
 was much shock and outrage and gnashing of teeth. There are a few other ex=
amples, over the years. But mostly banks do what the market wants, rather t=
han what they are technically allowed to do and what is economically best f=
or them.
You might find this troubling: It means that the investors are right (these=
 are bonds that have to be paid back) and the regulators are wrong. It mean=
s that these instruments are in some sense not=C2=A0real=C2=A0capital; they=
 don=E2=80=99t have the loss-absorbing flexibility that regulators think th=
ey have. In a crisis, these instruments might not protect depositors and ta=
xpayers as much as the regulators hope.
And so   Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Tasos Vossos reports today:

Achim Wiechert=C2=A0was one of the many experts brought in to mend the brok=
en market for bank capital securities in the aftermath of the financial cri=
sis. He worries it could break again =E2=80=94 and he=E2=80=99s on a missio=
n to fix it.
The head of external funding at insurance giant=C2=A0Allianz SE=C2=A0is lob=
bying for one of the most far-reaching overhauls to Europe=E2=80=99s $235 b=
illion market for additional tier 1 bank debt since it was created more tha=
n a decade ago to prevent a rerun of 2008=E2=80=99s taxpayer-led bailouts. =
=E2=80=A6
Wiechert=E2=80=99s concern is that AT1s, which count as capital, will fail =
to buffer banks from another crisis. This isn=E2=80=99t a flaw of the bonds=
 themselves but of market behavior: Convention dictates that banks repay th=
e notes at their first call date, whether or not it makes economic sense.
And at a time when they really need the capital, in a crisis, lenders would=
 be even more compelled to follow those conventions, swallowing punitive de=
bt costs so they can show it=E2=80=99s business as usual. He argues that th=
e need to keep up appearances could plunge banks into trouble. =E2=80=A6
His solution is to take the decision on whether to repay AT1s early out of =
banks=E2=80=99 hands, and leave it up to market math. Either a replacement =
bond can be cheaper than a predetermined level or the bank will be barred a=
utomatically from exercising the call option.

Intuitively, in my Possibility 1, the bank should replace its current AT1 w=
ith a new, cheaper one. In my Possibility 2, the bank should=C2=A0not=C2=A0=
replace its current AT1 with a new, more expensive one: It should just leav=
e the old one outstanding, even if investors are disappointed. The goal of =
these securities is to disappoint investors sometimes. That=E2=80=99s why t=
hey work as capital.

