<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bitcoin hitman user experience</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are three classic problems that you migh=
t encounter=C2=A0if you try to use Bitcoin to pay for goods and services. T=
he first problem is that your Bitcoins might go astray: Bitcoin transaction=
s are irreversible and involve sending money to long complicated addresses,=
 and people are constantly trying to steal them. So if you send someone Bit=
coin to pay for something, there will probably be a typo in the address and=
 the person won=E2=80=99t get it and you=E2=80=99ll have to send it again a=
nd your first payment will just be permanently lost.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second problem is that Bitcoin is very vol=
atile, and even people who accept payment in Bitcoin tend not to=C2=A0<em>d=
enominate=C2=A0</em>it in Bitcoin. So if you send someone $100 worth of Bit=
coin to buy a $100 thing, the price of Bitcoin might drop 10% while you=E2=
=80=99re sending it, and then they=E2=80=99ll say =E2=80=9Cyou only sent me=
 $90=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99ll have to top them up with more Bitcoin.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The third classic problem is that, if you are =
using Bitcoin to pay for goods and services, there is a good chance that yo=
u are paying for something illegal, and Bitcoin payments are traceable. So =
if you send someone $16,000 worth of Bitcoin to buy a $16,000 thing, (1) so=
me of your money will go missing in transit, (2) the Bitcoins you send won=
=E2=80=99t be worth $16,000 and you=E2=80=99ll have to send some more, and =
(3) the $16,000 thing was a murder and now you are in prison.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">James Wan <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/33080201.255424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby=
1uZGdhL3ByL2RvY3Rvci1wbGVhZHMtZ3VpbHR5LWRhcmstd2ViLW11cmRlci1oaXJlLXBsb3Q/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa35939c8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">knows these problems well</a>:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On April 18, 2022, while in the Northern Distr=
ict of Georgia, Wan accessed a dark web marketplace from his cellular telep=
hone and submitted an order to have a hitman murder his girlfriend. The ord=
er included the victim=E2=80=99s name, address, Facebook account, license p=
late, and car description. In the order, Wan stated: =E2=80=9CCan take wall=
et phone and car. Shoot and go. Or take car.=E2=80=9D Wan then electronical=
ly transferred a 50% downpayment of approximately $8,000 worth of Bitcoin t=
o the dark web marketplace.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two days later, Wan messaged the marketplace=
=E2=80=99s administrator, stating that the transferred Bitcoin did not show=
 up in his escrow account on the site. The next day, the marketplace admini=
strator asked Wan for the Bitcoin address to which Wan had sent the payment=
. In response, Wan identified the Bitcoin wallet address and provided a scr=
eenshot of the transaction. When the administrator said that the address Wa=
n provided was not in their system, Wan replied, =E2=80=9CDamn. I guess I l=
ost $8k. I=E2=80=99m sending $8k to escrow now.=E2=80=9D Wan then electroni=
cally transferred an additional Bitcoin payment worth approximately $8,000 =
to the marketplace. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">About a week later, on April 29, 2022, Wan ele=
ctronically transferred another payment of approximately $8,000 worth of Bi=
tcoin to the dark web marketplace to ensure his escrow account contained th=
e total required to complete the order. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On May 10, 2022, after the value of Bitcoin dr=
opped, Wan electronically transferred another payment of approximately $1,2=
00 worth of Bitcoin to the marketplace to ensure his escrow account still c=
ontained the total required to complete the order.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wan pleaded guilty this week. =E2=80=9CAfter s=
peaking with FBI agents, Wan canceled the order on the dark web marketplace=
,=E2=80=9D terrific. I wonder how many murder-for-hire contracts had to be =
repriced when crypto prices collapsed last year. Not zero!=C2=A0</p>
