<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose if you are a law enforcement officer=
 and a guy calls 911 and says =E2=80=9Csomeone stole my Bitcoins,=E2=80=9D =
you could just go to his house and arrest him? Or at least show up and ask =
him questions like =E2=80=9Cwhere did you last see your Bitcoins?=E2=80=9D =
and =E2=80=9Cdo you have any enemies?=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cis there any ch=
ance you acquired these Bitcoins by hacking a dark-web drug marketplace?=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/33080201.255424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyM=
y8xMC8xNy9jcnlwdG85MTEuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd4588d02" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
CNBC story</a> about a guy named Jimmy Zhong, who called 911 because someon=
e stole his Bitcoins, and the cops showed up and were like =E2=80=9Cokay bu=
t who did=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>steal the Bitcoins from,=E2=80=9D and he w=
as like =E2=80=9Coh Silk Road=E2=80=9D and they arrested him.=C2=A0No, I=E2=
=80=99m kidding, I=E2=80=99m condensing the timeline, and he didn=E2=80=99t=
 actually <em>say </em>that, but that <em>is </em>where=C2=A0he stole the B=
itcoins from, and they did ultimately arrest him for it. The scorecard here=
 is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The guy who stole hundreds of thousan=
ds of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of Zhong=E2=80=99s Bitcoins was never caught.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Zhong was sentenced to=C2=A0a year=
 in prison for stealing billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of Silk Road=E2=
=80=99s Bitcoins.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The guy who ran =
Silk Road was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3308=
0201.255424/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvUm9zc19VbGJyaWNodA/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB84e49bd0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">sentenced to life in prison</a>, mos=
tly for running a marketplace selling drugs for Bitcoins though also for tr=
ying to use Bitcoins to hire hitmen to do some murders.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lesson might be that if you are going to d=
o crypto crime, stealing from people who steal from people who run crypto d=
rug marketplaces is a better bet than running the marketplaces yourself. Th=
is is not any sort of advice at all.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Three other funny points from the CNBC story. =
One is that US law enforcement seized the Bitcoins that Zhong stole from Si=
lk Road (except for the ones that were stolen from him) and very cleverly o=
ffered to return them to their rightful owners, opening =E2=80=9Ca process =
that allowed victims of the hack to apply to get their bitcoin back.=E2=80=
=9D Again this is not legal advice, but do not fill out that application! N=
obody did:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nobody came forward to claim the l=
oot. That=E2=80=99s not surprising, given that users of Silk Road in 2012 w=
ere largely drug dealers and their customers.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two, the government then =E2=80=9Csold off the=
 stolen bitcoin and will keep the proceeds.=E2=80=9D Zhong=E2=80=99s lawyer=
s make the sensible point that, by stealing these Bitcoins from Silk Road a=
nd handing them over to the government years later, Zhong actually made the=
 government a lot of money:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf Jimmy had not stolen the coins and=
 the government had in fact seized them from [Silk Road operator Ross Ulbri=
cht] they would have sold them two years later in 2014 as they did with oth=
er coins.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At that point, the government =E2=80=9Cwould h=
ave gotten $320 a coin or made somewhere about $14 million,=E2=80=9D Bachne=
r said. =E2=80=9CNow, as a result of Jimmy having them, the government has =
gotten a $3 billion profit.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the last few years, a=C2=A0lot of people =
have made arguments with the essential form =E2=80=9CI am an investing geni=
us because I held Bitcoin from 2014 through 2021,=E2=80=9D but this particu=
lar one struck me as novel.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Three, here=E2=80=99s how BlockTrace cyberinte=
lligence investigator Shaun MaGruder knew that Zhong was the hacker:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">MaGruder said Zhong=E2=80=99s level of sophist=
ication was apparent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHe was navigating that keyboard like =
I=E2=80=99ve never seen someone navigate a keyboard,=E2=80=9D MaGruder said=
. =E2=80=9CHe didn=E2=80=99t have to use a mouse because he knew all the ho=
tkeys.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Watch out, investment banking analysts.</p>
