>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>pay interest, or=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<=
/em>pay them back after five to ten years, nothing happens: The holders of =
the AT1s can=E2=80=99t sue for their money or put the bank into bankruptcy;=
 everything is kind of voluntary. (This oversimplifies the mechanics, but n=
ot by too much.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The advantage of this structure is that banks =
can pitch it to investors as =E2=80=9Clook, a bond=E2=80=9D and pay a fairl=
y low interest rate, and they can pitch it to regulators as =E2=80=9Clook, =
equity=E2=80=9D and get a lot of regulatory capital credit. I <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33080201.255424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
