<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0<em>most=C2=A0</em>of the time invest=
ors are right: Most of the time banks pay their interest on AT1s, and repay=
 them at the =E2=80=9Cfirst call date,=E2=80=9D the date, five to ten years=
 after issuance, when the market=C2=A0<em>expects=C2=A0</em>them to mature.=
 (Technically they have no maturity date because the bank=C2=A0<em>can=C2=
=A0</em>keep them outstanding forever, but the bank usually pays them back =
at the first call.) In particular, because interest rates move, when an AT1=
 reaches its first call date, there are two possibilities:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Interest rates have gone down,<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
