!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0so the bank can repay the AT1 and replace it with a new AT1 with =
a lower interest rate, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Interest=
 rates have gone up, so if the bank repaid the AT1 it would have to replace=
 it with a new AT1 with a=C2=A0<em>higher=C2=A0</em>interest rate.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Possibility 1, the bank can and should repa=
y the AT1 (and do a new cheaper one), and normally does. In Possibility 2, =
economically speaking, the bank=C2=A0<em>shouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>repay =
the AT1: It should keep it outstanding as cheap capital, rather than repayi=
ng it and issuing new, more expensive capital.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in fact, in Possibility 2, banks almost al=
ways=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>repay their AT1s, because that is more polite to=
 AT1 investors, and banks want the goodwill of AT1 investors, because they =
will be coming back to them for capital. When <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33080201.255424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDItMTMvc2FudGFuZGVyLWRpZG4tdC1wYXktaXRzLW=
